In the current version, there are two ways you can accomplish this, depending on where it is more useful to hook into the datatableview code.

``datatableview.defaultDataTableOptions`` is an object which is extended on a per-object basis with the select and options object provided to ``datatableview.initialize()``, so you can add a callback like this directly to the default set:

```javascript
// The 'ajax' entry in this object does not exist yet, but if you supply a partial set of options
// like I do below, it will be extended later when the init code wants to add in the url, etc.
//
// Be aware that you're modifying the default options for all tables that initialize on this page!
// Also, be sure you're doing this after the datatableview.js has been included, but before any
// datatables are initialized (e.g., probably don't want to put this in document.onReady)
datatableview.defaultDataTableOptions.ajax = {
    data: function(d){
        d.name = 'Joe';
        return d;
    }
};
```

Alternatively, and if you need per-table controls, you can provide a ``datatableview.finalizeOptions(datatable, options)`` callback, which is called after ``datatableview.initialize()`` is completely done setting up the built-in options from the template-rendered table.  You can inspect the table object to make sure you changing the right one, etc.

```javascript
$(function(){
    datatableview.finalizeOptions = function(datatable, options){
        // options.ajax is already fully formed in this scenario.
        options.ajax.data = function(d){
            d.name = 'Joe';
        };
        return options;  // Always return the options
    };
```

