@matt-gardner your second suggestion won't work for our use case since we want to run the stacked LSTMs once, but downstream use two different linear combinations with different weights of the layers.  It's also too restrictive for future potential use cases.

I could modify the code to fit the seq2seq abstraction in the stacked case by returning `(batch_size, timesteps, embedding_dim * num_layers)` but that requires a lot of clunky packing/unpacking only to undo it later where we need to use each layer separately.

I don't see how to use a pytorch RNN in this case since it doesn't support returning multiple layers, and would really like to reuse all sorting/stateful stuff in the current code.  Any suggestions about how to do that without cutting and pasting a lot of code or massively refactoring are appreciated.

> I think I still need convincing here that the approach being taken for activation is legitimate.

@mcg1969, I do believe the approach is legitimate.  Subprocessing to `/bin/sh` or `cmd.exe` is unfortunately but cleanly the requirement of having `activate.d` scripts be `.sh` or `.bat`.  We *do* execute each script, and if they have side effects other than environment variable changes, those side effects *will* be applied.

The optimization to call `exec` from the composed script isn't as clean, and I also don't think it buys us much.  Right now on unix, we fork a python process, subprocess to a generated script to activate, and then fall back to the python process to exec to the target executable.  The alternative you suggest is to fork a python process, exec to a generated script to activate, and then exec again to the target executable.  I would be shocked if that optimization gains more than 50 ms.  The process flow as coded here so far is the process flow we'd ultimately want to get to once we have #6820.

